lliers-en-Gâtinais, Loiret, Centre-Val-de-Loire, France":"Auvilliers-en-Gâtinais, Loiret, Centre, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Garlande","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>gerlond</i>, <i>ger(e)land</i>, <i>garlond</i> ‘metal chaplet, crown, coronet; wreath’, probably a nickname denoting a habitual wearer of such items, or a metonymic occupational name for a maker of them.","English: perhaps from the Old French personal name <i>Gerland</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Garuland</i>, probably from <i>garw-</i> ‘war-gear; prepared(ness)’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’; the first element of the French name may instead be from a name beginning with <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’).","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>lond</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>gāra</i> + <i>land</i>, <i>lond</i>), for someone who lived ‘(at the) triangular piece of land’. Compare   Garfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerland","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Garland  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Garfield","meanings":["English (Midlands): topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country, field’ (Old English <i>gār</i> + <i>feld</i>), for someone who lived by a triangular piece of land.","English: alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Carville   (a name of Norman origin), with excrescent final <i>-d</i>.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Gartland","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Garland  .","Irish (northern Leinster and southern Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Gearnúin</b>, a patronymic from the Norman personal name   Gernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabelle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabelle de Garlande was born about 1193, in Gournay, Seine-et-Oise, France, her father, Guillaume de Garlande III, was 55 and her mother, Alix de Chatillon, was 23. She married Seigneur de Gatinais Jean de Beaumont-en-Gâtinais Sr de Villemomble in April 1214, in Auvilliers-en-Gâtinais, Loiret, Centre, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 7 January 1249, at the age of 57."},"et":{"ABT 1193–7 JAN 1249/1255":"umbes 1193–7. jaanuar 1249","1193–1249":"1193–1249","1190–1256":"1190–1256","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1172–1216":"1172–1216","1190":"1190",